		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Flat Earth Society</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="dablink">"Flat Earth Society" redirects here. For the Belgian band, see <a href="/wiki/Flat_Earth_Society_(band)" title="Flat Earth Society (band)">Flat Earth Society (band)</a>.</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:302px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Azimuthal_Equidistant_N90.jpg" class="image" title="A rendered picture of the Flat Earth model."><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/17/Azimuthal_Equidistant_N90.jpg/300px-Azimuthal_Equidistant_N90.jpg" width="300" height="300" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Azimuthal_Equidistant_N90.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
A rendered picture of the Flat Earth model.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The <b>Flat Earth Society</b> (also known as the International Flat Earth Society or International Flat Earth Research Society) is an <a href="/wiki/Organization" title="Organization">organization</a> that furthers the belief that the <a href="/wiki/Earth" title="Earth">Earth</a> is flat rather than a sphere. The modern organization was founded by Englishman <a href="/w/index.php?title=Samuel_Shenton&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Samuel Shenton (page does not exist)">Samuel Shenton</a> in 1956<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup>, and later led by <a href="/wiki/Charles_K._Johnson" title="Charles K. Johnson">Charles K. Johnson</a>, who based the organization out of his home in <a href="/wiki/Lancaster,_California#Recreation_and_culture" title="Lancaster, California">Lancaster</a>, <a href="/wiki/California" title="California">California</a>. After Johnson’s death in 2001, the Flat Earth Society weakened and decentralized, but there are recent attempts to create a more unified and worldwide movement.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
